    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Spear-phishing, a type of phishing that's specifically tailored to target specific individuals, can be quite sneaky, like a well-crafted trap set by a cunning goblin. You want your staff to be vigilant, so here are some red flags and social engineering tactics to watch out for:\n\nFirstly, be wary of emails that create a sense of urgency, like a goblin trying to distract you while they snatch your lunch. Phishers often use time-sensitive language, claiming that an account will be suspended or a deadline is approaching. Your staff should be cautious of emails that ask for sensitive information, like login credentials or financial details, and never provide this information via email, especially if the email is unsolicited.\n\nAnother tactic to watch out for is the use of personalization, like a goblin who's done their research on you. Phishers may use the recipient's name, job title, or department to make the email appear more legitimate. Your staff should also be cautious of emails that contain grammatical errors or poor spelling, as these can be a sign of a phishing attempt.\n\nWhen it comes to links, be wary of emails that ask you to click on a link to verify your identity or complete a task. Ph",
